<p>Postcard (2 1/2 cent). Postmarks ‘NUENEN 8-12 V / 3 JUL 85’ and ‘EINDHOVEN 10-11V / 3 JUL 85’. The address reads: ‘WelEd Heer A. Kerssemakers Simonis/ <hi rend="italics">Eindhoven</hi>’ (Kerssemakers was married to Josephina Dymphina Simonis).</p>
                                    
                                
                    	</note>
                    
                </listAnnotation>
                <listAnnotation xml:lang="en" type="ogtnotes">
                    
                </listAnnotation>
                <listAnnotation xml:lang="en" type="notes">
                    
                        <note n="1" xml:id="note-t-1">
                            

<p><rs type="person" ref="bio.xml#_816">Willem van de Wakker</rs>, previously indirectly referred to in <ref target="let469.xml">letter 469</ref>. This amateur painter was a telegraph operator in the post office in Nuenen and lived at what was then no. 253 Rozemarijnstraat, district B (now Jan van Lieshoutstraat) in Eindhoven.</p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
                        <note n="2" xml:id="note-t-2">
                            

<p>Van Gogh probably means <rs type="person" ref="bio.xml#_451">Joseph van der Harten</rs>. He had a brewery in Vrijstraat in Eindhoven and was a friend of <rs type="person" ref="bio.xml#_449">Antoon Hermans</rs> (whom Van Gogh also knew). He stuffed animals. Cf. Jack van Hoek, ‘Over een kerkuil en een kalong’, <hi rend="italics">Drijehornickels</hi> 29-3 (2020), pp. 33-36. </p>
                        </note>
                        
                            

                        
                    
